<paragraph blockId="52.[125,1172,1221,1501]" pageId="52" pageNumber="2970">
<bibRefCitation author="Ananthakrishnan TN" box="[125,411,1221,1245]" pageId="52" pageNumber="2970" pagination="113 - 138" refId="ref32428" refString="Ananthakrishnan TN. 1967. Studies on new and little known Indian Thysanoptera. Oriental Insects 1: 113 - 138." type="journal article" year="1967">Ananthakrishnan (1967)</bibRefCitation>
proposed a sub-genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ananthakrishnan" authorityYear="1968" box="[680,815,1221,1245]" class="Insecta" family="Thysanoptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Saucrothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="52" pageNumber="2970" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[680,815,1221,1245]" italics="true" pageId="52" pageNumber="2970">Saucrothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
for a single species from 
<collectingCountry box="[1112,1172,1221,1245]" name="India" pageId="52" pageNumber="2970">India</collectingCountry>
with antennal segment III very similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mound &amp; Minaei" authorityYear="2007" box="[613,695,1253,1277]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Podothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="52" pageNumber="2970" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="barrowi">
<emphasis box="[613,695,1253,1277]" italics="true" pageId="52" pageNumber="2970">barrowi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, these two are not likely to be closely related, because the Indian species, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ananthakrishnan" authorityYear="1967" box="[629,739,1285,1309]" class="Insecta" family="Thysanoptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Saucrothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="52" pageNumber="2970" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="scitulus">
<emphasis box="[629,739,1285,1309]" italics="true" pageId="52" pageNumber="2970">S. scitulus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, has the typical tooth-like tubercle at the inner apex of the fore tibiae that is found in many 
<taxonomicName box="[768,971,1317,1341]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Podothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="52" pageNumber="2970" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[768,881,1317,1341]" italics="true" pageId="52" pageNumber="2970">Podothrips</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
from around the world. In contrast, all members of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ritchie" authorityYear="1974" box="[580,703,1349,1373]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Podothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="52" pageNumber="2970" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="australis">
<emphasis box="[580,703,1349,1373]" italics="true" pageId="52" pageNumber="2970">P. australis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group discussed here lack this tubercle, and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mound &amp; Minaei" authorityYear="2007" box="[177,292,1381,1405]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Podothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="52" pageNumber="2970" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="barrowi">
<emphasis box="[177,292,1381,1405]" italics="true" pageId="52" pageNumber="2970">P. barrowi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is probably an Australian endemic derived from within this group. It is the only species discussed here that has the metathoracic sternopleural sutures developed, apart from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ritchie" authorityYear="1974" box="[261,386,1445,1469]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Podothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="52" pageNumber="2970" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="australis">
<emphasis box="[261,386,1445,1469]" italics="true" pageId="52" pageNumber="2970">P. australis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Kruger" baseAuthorityYear="1890" box="[450,579,1445,1469]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Podothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="52" pageNumber="2970" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lucasseni">
<emphasis box="[450,579,1445,1469]" italics="true" pageId="52" pageNumber="2970">P. lucasseni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Unlike so many of the species in this genus, the apical antennal segments are brown not yellow.
</paragraph>
