<paragraph blockId="52.[125,1172,1629,1685]" lastBlockId="53.[138,1185,137,257]" lastPageId="53" lastPageNumber="2971" pageId="52" pageNumber="2970">
This is a widespread Asian species that is sometimes associated with sugar cane or even rice. It is recorded by 
<bibRefCitation author="Ritchie JM" box="[396,568,1661,1685]" pageId="52" pageNumber="2970" pagination="261 - 282" refId="ref34477" refString="Ritchie JM. 1974. A revision of the grass-living genus Podothrips (Thysanoptera: Phlaeothripidae). Journal of Entomology B 43: 261 - 282." type="journal article" year="1974">Ritchie (1974)</bibRefCitation>
from Hawaii to 
<collectingCountry box="[772,908,1661,1685]" name="Bangladesh" pageId="52" pageNumber="2970">Bangladesh</collectingCountry>
, with both 
<emphasis box="[1048,1171,1661,1685]" italics="true" pageId="52" pageNumber="2970">hawaiiensis</emphasis>
Moulton and 
<emphasis box="[309,380,137,160]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="2971">oryzae</emphasis>
Priesner placed as synonyms. It differs from all of the Australian species in this genus in the character states indicated in the key (
<figureCitation box="[879,994,169,193]" captionStart="Figures 59–65" captionStartId="17.[138,207,1609,1628]" captionTargetBox="[138,1185,794,1573]" captionTargetId="figure-223@17.[138,1186,794,1573]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="Figures 59–65. (59) Haplothrips victoriensis, head and pronotum. (60) H. victoriensis, pelta. (61) Podothrips ardis, head and pronotum. (62) P. australis, head and pronotum. (63) P. australis, prosternites. (64) P. lucasseni, fore tibia. (65) P. barrowi, head and pronotum." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5233666" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5233666/files/figure.png" pageId="53" pageNumber="2971">Figure 64</figureCitation>
), and also in the uniform brown body and femora contrasting with the yellow tibiae. Two small females have been studied from Darwin.
</paragraph>
